Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday! Welcome to our 9th Weekly Dose of Optimism. I hope you=E2=80=
=99re on a beach somewhere, one eye shut squinting against the glare on you=
r phone to read about all of the incredible things your fellow humans pulle=
d off this week.
This Weekly Dose of Optimism is brought to you by=E2=80=A6 MarketerHire [ h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/78549c87-ef5a-4af1-bcc5-132211a85224?r=3D9p0gt=
 ]
Let=E2=80=99s say you=E2=80=99re feeling optimistic enough about your busin=
ess that you want to invest in growth, but you don=E2=80=99t want to lock y=
ourself into a long hiring process and full-time hires given the uncertain =
market conditions. MarketerHire [ https://substack.com/redirect/78549c87-ef=
5a-4af1-bcc5-132211a85224?r=3D9p0gt ] is for you.
With MarketerHire [ https://substack.com/redirect/78549c87-ef5a-4af1-bcc5-1=
32211a85224?r=3D9p0gt ], you can find and hire pre-vetted expert marketers =
in less than 48 hours. Staying lean has never been more important =E2=80=94=
 with MarketerHire, you can easily scale your marketing team up or down dep=
ending on the needs of your business. There are no long-term contracts and =
the first 5 hours of any engagement are risk-free.
Support The Weekly Dose of Optimism and find flexible expert marketing tale=
nt by checking out MarketerHire.
(1)  [ https://substack.com/redirect/af5996ee-991a-4c56-9d2d-8a8e45e786c9?r=
=3D9p0gt ]If Humans Went Extinct, Would a Similar Species Evolve? [ https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/af5996ee-991a-4c56-9d2d-8a8e45e786c9?r=3D9p0gt ]
By William MacAskill [ https://substack.com/redirect/f3d13d71-1515-4f03-9c3=
b-59a05c3fe8d6?r=3D9p0gt ] for Wired
We therefore cannot be confident that, were human civilization to end, some=
 other technologically capable species would eventually take our place. And=
 even if you think that there is a 90 percent chance this would happen, the=
 remaining risk of the permanent end of civilization would still be great e=
nough that reducing it should be a pressing moral priority.
Does the Fermi Paradox - the conflict between the lack of evidence for extr=
aterrestrial life and the estimated high probability of its existence - mak=
e you feel optimistic or anxious? Whether life exists far out there in the =
universe or not, it remains that the existence of human life on earth, math=
ematically speaking, is quite extraordinary. Will MacAskill, one of the ori=
ginators of the Effective Altruism movement and a proponent of longtermism,=
 explores the whether or not another a similar species would evolve if huma=
ns went extinct (nuclear war, climate disaster, etc.) His take: =E2=80=9Cif=
 we mess this up, we mess this up forever.=E2=80=9D Not exactly a comfortin=
g thought, but it does make you feel how special a responsibility we=E2=80=
=99ve all been given.
(2) China rises to first place in most cited papers [ https://substack.com/=
redirect/68e6ffc6-cea1-48fe-a0fb-b5dbd152fc29?r=3D9p0gt ]
Jeffrey Brainard [ https://substack.com/redirect/7f5593b9-85dc-48f6-9815-c8=
d6a676519f?r=3D9p0gt ] and Dennis Normile [ https://substack.com/redirect/c=
fdbc906-9671-45c8-903c-d7ba1c0cd57d?r=3D9p0gt ] for Science
For the first time, China has slightly edged out the United States in the n=
umber of most cited papers, a key measure of research impact, according to =
a Japanese science policy institute. The milestone provides fresh evidence =
that China=E2=80=99s scholarship, known for its burgeoning quantity, is cat=
ching up in quality as well.
China, for the first time, has inched past the U.S. in the number of most c=
ited papers. China has outnumbered the U.S. in the quantity of research it =
has produced for a number of years, but the citations measurement is import=
ant because it shows that quality of China=E2=80=99s research may also have=
 improved. There is still some skepticism around this measurement =E2=80=94=
 research paper mills, incestuous citation rings, etc., all discussed by No=
ah Smith here [ https://substack.com/redirect/db27348c-6c63-4d2f-beef-f3974=
3c27324?r=3D9p0gt ] =E2=80=94 but it=E2=80=99s another sign that China is g=
aining in the =E2=80=9Cscience race.=E2=80=9D
On its face, this isn=E2=80=99t an optimistic story from the western perspe=
ctive, but it is a good example of the kind of optimism we write about here=
=2E The David Deutsch Principle of Optimi=
sm states that: =E2=80=9CAll evils a=
re caused by insufficient knowledge.=E2=80=9D
Knowledge is becoming more widely available on the American side, too. On T=
hursday, the White House responded: Breakthroughs for All: Delivering Equit=
able Access to America=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Research [ https://substack.com/redir=
ect/eadba24a-7ac0-4eae-bfc4-a18bb5b2f6b4?r=3D9p0gt ]
The Biden Administration published a new policy around access to federally-=
funded research. There were two major changes:
Eliminating the optional 12-month publication embargo for federally funded =
peer-reviewed research articles.
Making data published in peer-reviewed research articles immediately availa=
ble upon publication.
What this means in practice is that tax-payer funded research can no longer=
 sit behind a paywall in scientific journals. The policy changes were desig=
ned to bring transparency and increased accessibility to the American scien=
tific discovery process. Perhaps more importantly, it is yet another sign i=
n the past few weeks that the administration is focused on revitalizing the=
 American scientific research engine and leaning into America=E2=80=99s rel=
ative strengths: openness and bottoms-up innovation.=20
(3) Forever Chemicals No More? PFAS Are Destroyed With New Technique [ http=
s://substack.com/redirect/7f539941-3d10-444c-9718-67eded96eae3?r=3D9p0gt ]
Carl Zimmer [ https://substack.com/redirect/0a8ee64a-7d21-4eaa-8e74-8e554d5=
f9e27?r=3D9p0gt ] for The New York Times
A team of scientists has found a cheap, effective way to destroy so-called =
forever chemicals, a group of compounds that pose a global threat to human =
health=E2=80=A6The chemicals =E2=80=94 known as PFAS [ https://substack.com=
/redirect/7cf94cef-452b-4e3d-85ce-96a1e4b1f042?r=3D9p0gt ], or per- and pol=
yfluoroalkyl substances =E2=80=94 are found in a spectrum of products and c=
ontaminate water and soil around the world=E2=80=A6In a study, published [ =
https://substack.com/redirect/96c7e3ef-b567-4278-953f-37cc6107579b?r=3D9p0g=
t ] Thursday in the journal Science, a team of researchers rendered PFAS mo=
lecules harmless by mixing them with two inexpensive compounds at a low boi=
l. In a matter of hours, the PFAS molecules fell apart.
If you=E2=80=99ve ever seen the 2018 Netflix documentary, The Devil We Know=
 [ https://substack.com/redirect/db0911e0-fd99-4a3d-adc8-1de7d5de314c?r=3D9=
p0gt ], this story should bring you some measure of relief. The doc investi=
gated the health hazards from PFAs, a key ingredient found in Teflon which =
can be found in many household items, most famously the non-stick pan. The =
tricky thing with PFAs is that they are remarkably hard to get rid of and c=
an contaminate water, soil, and the environment over long periods of time. =
Historically, we=E2=80=99ve had little recourse in destroying PFAs, but thi=
s new study shows that a relatively =E2=80=9Csimple=E2=80=9D methodology ma=
y provide a cheap, effective way to destroy so-called forever chemicals. St=
ill, the researchers warn that the most effective solution in lowering PFA =
levels is reducing new PFAs introduced into the environment.
(4) Startup=E2=80=99s Hydrogen Breakthrough May Give New Life to Coal Plant=
s [ https://substack.com/redirect/c3cb13a5-8c74-4cc2-8f9e-4d7d734369e7?r=3D=
9p0gt ]
Swati Pandey [ https://substack.com/redirect/03b3b29b-9a9c-49f2-8ae9-0c126e=
a2c0bf?r=3D9p0gt ] for Bloomberg
Bottled hydrogen and oxygen are fed into a glass cylinder containing the se=
cret catalyst, which quickly turns orange as it heats up to around 700 degr=
ees Celsius (1,292 Fahrenheit). If the technology can scale up, it could ul=
timately allow power plant operators that burn coal to retrofit generators =
to run on green hydrogen without having to construct a completely new plant=
=2E
Chalk it up as founding myth lore, but whether this startup =E2=80=9Cstumbl=
ed=E2=80=9D on a new way to convert hydrogen into heat without burning it o=
r not is less important than the discovery itself. The technology, once sca=
led for commercial use, could allow coal-powered power plants to retrofit g=
enerators to run on green hydrogen, instead of building new green plants fr=
om scratch.=20
Here=E2=80=99s a non-scientist take on why this is important: power-plants =
run on generators =E2=80=94> generators are powered by steam engines =E2=80=
=94> steam is created when water is heated =E2=80=94> traditionally, heat i=
s created by burning coal =E2=80=94> carbon dioxide is a biproduct of burni=
ng coal =E2=80=94> CO2 is a major contributor to greenhouse effect. The bre=
akthrough here is that, by using a secret catalyst, the startup, Star Scien=
tific, can turn hydrogen and oxygen directly into steam, without burning an=
ything. The process can be plugged into existing coal-powered plants =E2=80=
=94 ripping out the coal and replacing it with Star Scientific=E2=80=99s fr=
ench press-like device =E2=80=94 making the whole thing faster and more eff=
icient than building new plants.=20
(5) We Need to Talk About How Good A.I. Is Getting [ https://substack.com/r=
edirect/c3ee5561-2c11-437b-a854-fe253bef95c7?r=3D9p0gt ]
Kevin Roose [ https://substack.com/redirect/73c08343-aa10-42f3-b70c-e8d7cc5=
024b6?r=3D9p0gt ] for The New York Times
Some of that progress has been slow and steady =E2=80=94 bigger models with=
 more data and processing power behind them yielding slightly better result=
s.
But other times, it feels more like the flick of a switch =E2=80=94 impossi=
ble acts of magic suddenly becoming possible.
This week, Stable Diffusion announced its public open source release [ http=
s://substack.com/redirect/9ab8103b-86cf-4f1d-87df-dae5f72f3022?r=3D9p0gt ] =
=E2=80=94 you can play with it here [ https://substack.com/redirect/2ee99c5=
4-452f-4ae2-863e-7235b174a96b?r=3D9p0gt ]. The AI image generator built by =
independent researchers is the latest in the AI hot streak that Roose descr=
ibes in the article, which includes Open AI=E2=80=99s GPT-3 and DALL=E2=80=
=A2E 2, AlphaGo and AlphaFold from Google=E2=80=99s DeepMind, and Googles L=
aMDA, which convinced an engineer [ https://substack.com/redirect/00bd44ea-=
4880-4b7f-971f-320bd85676cd?r=3D9p0gt ] it was sentient. Recently, John Car=
mack, the creator of Doom and former CTO of Meta=E2=80=99s Oculus, announce=
d his new startup, Keen Technologies, which is tackling Artificial General =
Intelligence.
After a long period in which AI was =E2=80=9Cjust a few years away,=E2=80=
=9D it seems that the =E2=80=9Cgolden age=E2=80=9D of AI is upon us. It sho=
uld generate a flood of benefits and challenges alike, including what some =
believe to be the biggest existential risk to humanity: adversarial AI that=
 wipes out the human race. Roose argues that the technology is coming eithe=
r way, and encourages everyone to read up and get prepared.=20
Bonus: Techbio Taxonomy [ https://substack.com/redirect/afbe3372-90ba-49ea-=
b16a-1dbe971d68e0?r=3D9p0gt ] by Elliot Hershberg [ https://substack.com/re=
direct/f33d8bea-df23-443c-96a3-154b6da6a716?r=3D9p0gt ] for Not Boring
The world of biotech is beginning to look a lot more like tech. In Monday=
=E2=80=99s piece, Elliot breaks down the four defining characteristics of T=
echbio companies and why they=E2=80=99re important. My takeaway: over the n=
ext decade, we=E2=80=99re going to see a surge of entrepreneurial talent un=
leashed on solving some really big health, food, and materials challenges b=
y programming atoms the way the last decade=E2=80=99s entrepreneurs program=
med bits.
